#: ../../firewall.rst:5
msgid "Firewall"
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:7
msgid ""
"Firewall zones categorize network interfaces, defining trust boundaries, "
"while firewall rules dictate traffic handling between zones. Zones "
"organize network segments, and rules enforce security policies by "
"specifying conditions for permitted or denied actions. Together, they "
"allow the definition and application of rules for network traffic within "
"the firewall."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:14
msgid "Zones and policies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:16
msgid ""
"In a firewall system, zones and policies are fundamental concepts that "
"help manage network security by controlling the flow of traffic between "
"different segments of a network. A zone in a firewall represents a "
"specific network segment with its own level of trustworthiness. For "
"instance, a common setup might include zones like WAN (Wide Area Network)"
" representing the external, untrusted network (usually the internet) and "
"LAN (Local Area Network) representing the internal, trusted network "
"(devices within a private home or organization). Each zone has its own "
"set of security rules and policies that dictate how traffic can flow to "
"and from that zone."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:23
msgid ""
"Policies in a firewall define the rules and actions that determine how "
"traffic is handled between different zones. These rules specify which "
"type of traffic is allowed, denied, or monitored based on predefined "
"security criteria"
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:26
msgid "Default zones:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:28
msgid ""
"**WAN (Wide Area Network):** represents the external, untrusted network "
"(e.g., the internet)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:29
msgid ""
"**LAN (Local Area Network):** represents the internal, trusted network "
"(e.g., devices within a private home or organization)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:31
msgid "Accepted traffic:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:33
msgid ""
"**from LAN to WAN:** traffic from devices within the LAN zone to the WAN "
"zone is allowed, enabling internal devices to access the internet."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:34
msgid ""
"**from LAN to firewall itself:** traffic from LAN devices to the firewall"
" itself is permitted, facilitating communication for various purposes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:35
msgid ""
"**From LAN to LAN itself:** traffic between devices within the LAN zone "
"is allowed, enabling internal devices to communicate with each other."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:37
msgid "Denied traffic:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:39
msgid ""
"**From WAN to firewall itself:** traffic from the WAN zone to the "
"firewall itself is denied, preventing unauthorized external access "
"attempts."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:40
msgid ""
"**From WAN to WAN itself:** direct communication between external "
"networks (WAN to WAN) is denied, isolating different external entities "
"for enhanced security."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:42
msgid ""
"In this configuration, the firewall regulates traffic between the WAN and"
" LAN zones, allowing internal devices to access the internet and "
"communicate internally while maintaining security by blocking direct "
"external access to the firewall and preventing communication between "
"external networks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:44
msgid ""
"Default zones can't be deleted but the network administrator can change "
"existing policies or create new zones."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:49
msgid "Rules"
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:51
msgid ""
"Firewall rules define how network traffic is segmented and controlled "
"between different zones. Firewalls acts as barriers between trusted "
"internal networks and untrusted external networks, such as the internet. "
"These rules specify which traffic is allowed, denied, or monitored based "
"on predefined security policies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:55
msgid ""
"The order of rules is important; the first matching rule is applied, "
"determining the fate of the network packet."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:57
msgid "The page is organized into three tabs, each serving a specific purpose:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:59
msgid ""
"``Forward rules`` tab: thiis tab is dedicated to configuring rules for "
"data packets moving between different zones in the network."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:60
msgid ""
"``Input rules`` tab: this tab is dedicated to configuring rules for "
"incoming packets destined for the firewall itself."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:61
msgid ""
"``Output rules`` tab: this tab is dedicated to configuring rules for "
"packets emitted by the firewall."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:63
msgid ""
"Locate the button to add a new rule, click on it to initiate the rule "
"creation process. Fill in the following fields for the new rule:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:66
msgid ""
"``Status``: enable or disable the rule based on your requirements. By "
"default the rule is enabled during creation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:67
msgid "``Rule name``: assign a descriptive name to identify the rule."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:68
msgid ""
"``Source address``: enter one or more IPv4/IPv6 addresses or networks. "
"Leave unselected for any source address. This field is not present for "
"``Output rules``, as the source address is always the firewall itself."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:70
msgid ""
"``Source zone``: specify the traffic source zone. Choose a specific zone "
"or select 'Any' to include traffic from any zone."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:71
msgid ""
"``Destination address``: enter one or more IPv4/IPv6 addresses or "
"networks. Leave unselected for any destination address. This field is not"
" present for ``Input rules``, as the destination address is always the "
"firewall itself."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:73
msgid ""
"``Destination zone``: specify the traffic destination zone. Choose a "
"specific zone. Bear in mind that the source and destination zones can't "
"be the same."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:74
msgid ""
"``Destination service``: select from the list or choose 'Custom' to enter"
" specific ports and select protocols."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:75
msgid ""
"``Action``: define the action when the rule conditions are met: * "
"``Accept``: accept the network traffic. * ``Reject``: block the traffic "
"and notify the sender host. * ``Drop``: block the traffic, packets are "
"dropped and no notification is sent to the sender host."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:79
msgid ""
"``Rule position``: decide whether to add the rule to the bottom or top of"
" the rule list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:80
msgid ""
"``Logging``: indicate whether traffic matching this rule should be "
"logged. The log entry will include the rule name as a prefix."
msgstr ""

#: ../../firewall.rst:81
msgid ""
"``Tags``: optionally, add tags for organizational purposes. Note that the"
" 'automated' tag is reserved for system use."
msgstr ""

